<paragraph id="E5B94281C0F2B0444A188E48D87A8C17" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421">Occurs as terrestrial in lowland and montane rainforests.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F4C5CCF8E9A3DB816D018091A5DA5AD7" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph id="110FCC067685FC03C99AEDAA744C1DE4" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DE77E994A9881AB7F022EE782FE4A5A3" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421">
This species is easily recognizable by the subdimorphic leaves and orangish glands present on receptacle (
<bibRefCitation id="5CB614A0F07898CCC22F9417ACECE678" author="Smith, A. R." journalOrPublisher="University of California Publications in Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421" pagination="1 - 38" title="Taxonomy of ThelypterissubgenusSteiropteris, including Glaphyropteris (Pteridophyta)" volume="76" year="1980">Smith 1980</bibRefCitation>
). The closest species appears to be 
<taxonomicName id="E33974257F635929EEE403AB2E46AFC8" genus="T." lsidName="T. (Steiropteris) leprieurii" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421" rank="species" species="leprieurii" subGenus="Steiropteris">T. (Steiropteris) leprieurii</taxonomicName>
(Hook.) R.M.Tryon, which can also present dimorphic fronds (
<bibRefCitation id="127812C2C510100EEBADDF2175C24F88" author="Smith, A. R." journalOrPublisher="University of California Publications in Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="4421" pagination="1 - 38" title="Taxonomy of ThelypterissubgenusSteiropteris, including Glaphyropteris (Pteridophyta)" volume="76" year="1980">Smith 1980</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
